A federal USDA waiver will allow all enrolled virtual and hybrid Culpeper County Public School students to receive free breakfast and lunch, on the days school is in session, through December 31, 2020.

Hybrid students will have the ability to receive breakfast and lunch on the days that they are attending in person school. All virtual students, whether 100% virtual or hybrid students not attending school in person that day, will have the ability to receive breakfast and lunch through the schools Grab and Go locations.

If you have any questions please do not hesitate to contact your school's cafeteria manager or the Food Service Operations department at 540-825-8212x4557.

post_text:
CCPS complies with Virginia regulations regarding screening of children in public schools. Kindergarten children and those new to CCPS are screened in the following areas: hearing, vision, speech, voice and language, and fine and gross motor skills. Screenings will take place by the end of October for students who participate in the blended learning model as well as the 100% remote learning model. The screenings for students in the 100% remote learning model will be done via phone or video conference with parents.

Students in grades 3, 7, and 10 are required to be screened in vision and hearing. These screenings are scheduled to take place in January, 2021 for all students. However, if parents have a concern with their child's hearing or vision, they should contact their child's school for an earlier screening.

If students fail one or more screening, parents will be notified in writing. If you have questions about the screening process, please contact the Office of Special Education at (540) 825-3677, Extension 3134.

The CCPS Special Education Advisory Council (SEAC) will convene it's regularly scheduled meeting on Tuesday, May 5, 2020 at 6:30 pm. Nominations for SEAC members for the 2020-2021 school year will be accepted. Due to COVID-19 and social distancing practices, the meeting will be held via video conference with members and ex-officio members only.

If you would like to nominate yourself or someone else for SEAC membership or ask a question or provide public comment, please contact the SEAC Chair, Mrs. Toni Evans, at t_strauss@icloud.com. Nominations, questions and comments must be received by 4:00 pm on Tuesday, May 5. Questions and comments will be read during Public Comment and will be reflected in the meeting minutes. text:
The CCPS Special Education Advisory Council (SEAC) will convene it's regularly scheduled meeting on Tuesday, May 5, 2020 at 6:30 pm. Nominations for SEAC members for the 2020-2021 school year will be accepted. Due to COVID-19 and social distancing practices, the meeting will be held via video conference with members and ex-officio members only.

If you would like to nominate yourself or someone else for SEAC membership or ask a question or provide public comment, please contact the SEAC Chair, Mrs. Toni Evans, at t_strauss@icloud.com. Nominations, questions and comments must be received by 4:00 pm on Tuesday, May 5. Questions and comments will be read during Public Comment and will be reflected in the meeting minutes. Nominations will also be reflected in the meeting minutes and voting will take place at the next scheduled meeting.

post_text:
A Culpeper Middle School student was one of eight regional winners from across the state in the Virginia Municipal League “If I Were Mayor” essay contest. Seventh-grader Elle Crosley’s 500 word essay was judged the best in a region that included Culpeper!

Every year, VML hosts a contest which invites seventh graders from throughout the state to submit essays describing what they would do if they were mayor of their hometown. The students write an essay describing what change they would want to make in their community. Virginia Municipal League receives hundreds of entries. Elle was chosen the regional winner and will receive a plaque, certificate, and a check for $150!

Congratulations Elle Crosley!!

Important Changes to Breakfast and Lunch Pick-Up:

In response to parent input and in an effort to better serve CCPS students and families we are making the following change to our drive-through meal service for our students. On Monday, March 23rd students will receive a second breakfast with lunch that is for Tuesday morning. Beginning Tuesday, March 24th drive-through meal service will take place once each day Monday through Friday from 1130AM-130PM. Students will receive lunch for the day and breakfast for the following day.

Sites will continue to be: Emerald Hill Elementary School, Pearl Sample Elementary School, and Sycamore Park Elementary School.

Culpeper Human Services will be implementing this change at their Galbreath-Marshall location as well.

Fourth graders took the voyage to Jamestown and lived life through the eyes of a settler back in 1607. They visited replicas of a Powhatan village, climbed on board the Susan Constant, took a peek at the food that the settlers ate, and watched a musket being fired. This was a great hands-on experience for our students to see the work it took to live over 400 years ago.

CCPS changes Early Dismissal Times

The last three days of school for Culpeper County Public Schools for the 2018/2019 school year are Friday, May 24th, Tuesday, May 28th, and Wednesday, May 29th. These three days will be early dismissal.

Culpeper Schools will implement a new dismissal schedule starting on May 24th.

Secondary schools (CMS/FTBMS/CCHS/EVHS) will dismiss at 12:00 p.m.
Elementary Country Schools (EHES/PSES/AGRES) will dismiss at 12:45 p.m.
Elementary Town Schools (YES/SPES/FES) will dismiss at 1:15 p.m.

The Culpeper County School Board has scheduled a “TAB Time” for the FY’20 budget year for Monday, February 11th at 5:30 p.m. at the County Administration Office, 302 N. Main Street, Culpeper, VA.

TAB stands for “Talk about Budget,” when the School Board invites all members of the public to come to an informal session and share ideas or concerns about education needs and the school budget for school year 2019-20.

The School Board believes strongly that community input is vital to the budget process. All concerned Culpeper County citizens are encouraged to attend the February 11th “TAB Time.”

post_text: Culpeper County Public Schools will be assigning Chromebooks to all high school students for the Spring semester as part of our 1 to 1 initiative. Students will be allowed to take these Chromebooks home to assist in homework and other on-going assignments. We will be distributing these to students on Thursday, January 3rd at CCHS and Friday, January 4th at EVHS. Distribution times on those days will be from 9:00 to 11:00 am and 4:00 to 6:00 pm. Students should have received a device agreement form to be completed in order to take their Chromebook home. Please visit the CCPS Connect website linked from the main division webpage. Any additional questions or concerns should be directed to Donovan O'Brien, Director of Instructional Delivery at 540-825-3677 X3126.

post_text: Notice to All Parents - Culpeper County Public Schools complies with Virginia regulations regarding screening of children in public schools. For children in Kindergarten, grades 3, 7, & 10, Culpeper County Public Schools conducts hearing and vision screenings within 60 administrative days of the opening of school. In addition to hearing and vision screenings, children in Kindergarten and other students new to Culpeper County Public Schools are screened in the area of speech, voice and language and fine and gross motor skills. If students fail a screening, parents will be notified in writing. If you have questions about the screening process, please contact the Office of Special Education at 540-825-3677 ext. 3134.
